{"key":"processedPost-6256983","value":{"id":6256983,"first":6256808,"last":6260393,"when":1162921622,"utime":"11/07/06 07:47 PM","content":"That's a good point.  If the rye came from a feed store, it probably has fungicides in it, which means you can't grow from spores.  You'd have to use liquid culture or agar wedges to inoculate.<br />I've found the endospores to be in the dust and chaff that rinse off easily as long as you rinse the rye berries prior to the soak.  Of course, rinsing to remove the chaff and dust also prevents clumping of the grains later.<br />RR","title":"Re: issues with rye..."}}